{"id": "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_exp_twin-screw_wet_granulator_(tswg)", "document_id": "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing", "reactor_type": "twin-screw wet granulator (TSWG)", "reactor_name": "", "reactor_geometry": "", "reactor_material": "", "operating_conditions": [{"parameter": "mean_residence_time", "symbol": "MRT", "values": [60.0], "unit": "s", "range_min": null, "range_max": null}, {"parameter": "powder_flow_rate", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}, {"parameter": "turret_speed", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}, {"parameter": "fill_height", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}, {"parameter": "paddle_speed", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}], "dimensionless_numbers": [], "residence_time_data": {"mean_residence_time": {"values": [60.0], "unit": "s"}, "rtd_function_type": "E(t)"}, "tracer_experiment": {}, "flow_model": {}, "parameter_correlations": [], "key_findings": "MRT of TSWG is very short (typically less than one minute). Understanding RTD is crucial for ensuring robust control of continuous granulation processes. | RTD is influenced by critical parameters such as powder feed rate, screw speed, liquid-to-solid ratio, binder composition, and liquid feed addition method. Characterization of RTD is essential for robust control and regulatory compliance in continuous granulation processes. | Screw configuration has the most significant impact on mean residence time (MRT). Increasing the number of kneading elements leads to longer residence times. Artificial neural network (ANN)-based machine learning techniques have been used to predict MRT based on process parameters and screw configuration. A more systematic approach is needed to evaluate the influence of screw design on mixing and granulation in TSWG. | Reducing feed frame volume led to a substantial decrease in both the mean and variance of RTD. Gap size had minimal impact on RTD. Material distribution and back-mixing within the feed frame significantly affect tablet weight uniformity. High shear stress and prolonged residence time can lead to overlubrication and quality defects. | Reducing feed frame volume leads to a substantial decrease in both the mean and variance of RTD. Gap size has minimal impact. A linear correlation between bulk density and mean residence time (MRT) was established. RTD behavior is both material-dependent and equipment-dependent.", "provenance": [{"document_id": "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing", "chunk_ids": ["2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_9_32", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_9_33", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_9_34", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_10_35", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_10_36"]}]}
{"id": "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_exp_tablet_press", "document_id": "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing", "reactor_type": "tablet press", "reactor_name": "", "reactor_geometry": "", "reactor_material": "", "operating_conditions": [{"parameter": "paddle_speed", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}, {"parameter": "turret_speed", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}, {"parameter": "powder_flow_rate", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}, {"parameter": "fill_height", "symbol": null, "values": [], "unit": null, "range_min": null, "range_max": null}], "dimensionless_numbers": [], "residence_time_data": {}, "tracer_experiment": {}, "flow_model": {"type": "TIS model (combination of PFR and CSTR)", "parameters": {"PFR_section": "hopper to feed frame", "CSTR_section": "feed frame with rotating paddle wheel"}, "boundary_conditions": null}, "parameter_correlations": [], "key_findings": "Higher paddle speeds result in lower MRT and narrower MRT profile. Turret speed consistently leads to shorter MRT. Discrepancies in effects of paddle speed on MRT may be due to material properties and tracer selection. | TIS model is used for RTD in tablet press; PFR represents hopper to feed frame flow; CSTR represents feed frame with paddle wheel; RTD modeling integrated with PAT for quality assurance; DEM-based simulations used to study particle dynamics and segregation in feed frame. | RTD models for individual unit operations can be convoluted to derive a full process RTD model. Combined RTD models can be deconvoluted to separate individual unit operation RTD components. RTD is used for material traceability, lot definition, product quality prediction, material diversion, and continued process verification. RTD is applied in ongoing process monitoring during commercial production with low-level step changes in API concentration. | Challenges remain in tracer selection, data processing, and RTD model validation. Certain unit operations require a more systematic RTD evaluation. RTD methodology is gaining wider acceptance in the pharmaceutical industry, with increasing applications in flowsheet modeling and process optimization.", "provenance": [{"document_id": "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing", "chunk_ids": ["2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_10_37", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_10_38", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_11_39", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_11_40", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_12_41", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_13_42", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_14_43", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_14_44", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_14_45", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_understanding_and_development_of_residence_time_distribution_(rtd)_model_in_continuous_manufacturing_chunk_14_46", "2025_j_pharm_inv_-_underst